==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*xirtan'', from Indo-European ''*k̑erd-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[herte]], Old Saxon [[herta]] (Dutch [[hart]]), Old High German [[herza]] (German [[Herz]]), Old Norse [[hjarta]] (Swedish [[hjärta]]), Gothic [[𐌷𐌰𐌹𐍂𐍄𐍉]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[καρδία]], Latin [[cor]], Welsh [[craidd]], Russian [[сердце]], Lithuanian [[širdis]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'heoɹte/

===Noun===
'''heorte''' ''[[Wiktionary Appendix:Old English weak declension|weak]] f''
# the [[heart]], as an organ and as the seat of emotion
#:''Oþ ðæt him heortan blod foldan geseceþ'': until his heart's blood seek the earth.  (''Salomon & Saturn'')

